<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="sl">How Our Pricing Works</p>
    <h2>Countertop, over-the-range, built-in &mdash; three very different repair economics</h2>
    <div class="body-text">
      <p>Microwave repair economics depend heavily on the type of installation. A basic countertop microwave under $150 is often not worth repairing &mdash; a magnetron replacement can exceed the unit&rsquo;s value. But an over-the-range microwave above a range or a built-in unit integrated into cabinetry is a completely different calculation. Replacing those requires removing the old unit, purchasing a compatible replacement, and paying for installation &mdash; typically $400&ndash;$800+ total. Repair almost always wins on those units.</p>
      <p>We diagnose first. The $89 fee covers the full diagnosis including a high-voltage safety assessment. After diagnosis you get two numbers: labor and the specific OEM part. For countertop microwaves, we&rsquo;ll tell you honestly if repair doesn&rsquo;t make economic sense before proceeding.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="warning-block">
      <div class="warning-label">&#9888; High-voltage safety &mdash; do not attempt DIY</div>
      <p>Microwave ovens contain high-voltage capacitors rated at 2,100V or more that can hold a lethal charge even after the unit is unplugged. Magnetron, capacitor, and diode repairs require proper capacitor discharge procedures before any internal work. Our technicians are trained specifically in high-voltage microwave safety. Do not open a microwave interior beyond the glass door panel.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="type-grid">
      <div class="type-card">
        <h3>&#128291; Countertop</h3>
        <p>Freestanding units. Simple repairs (door latch, fuse, turntable) are cost-effective. Magnetron and control board replacements may not be worth it on budget units. We advise honestly after diagnosis.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <h3>&#127968; Over-the-range (OTR)</h3>
        <p>Mounted above range, serves as range hood. Almost always worth repairing &mdash; replacement requires a technician visit anyway. Add labor for dismounting the unit if needed for internal access.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <h3>&#127963;&#65039; Built-in / drawer</h3>
        <p>Integrated into cabinetry or as a drawer unit. Replacement requires cabinetry work and custom trim kits. Repair is almost always the better option. Higher labor for built-in access.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

