    <h2>What affects microwave repair cost in Los Angeles</h2>
    <div class="factors-grid">
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#128291;</div><h3>Countertop: repair vs. replace math</h3><p>Budget countertop microwaves ($100&ndash;$200) often don&rsquo;t make economic sense to repair when the magnetron or control board fails. We tell you this before ordering parts. Door latch, fuse, and turntable repairs on any unit usually make sense.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#127968;</div><h3>OTR and built-in: almost always repair</h3><p>An over-the-range or built-in microwave replacement requires professional installation and typically costs $400&ndash;$800+ including the unit, trim kit, and labor. Repair is almost always the better financial choice on these units.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#9888;&#65039;</div><h3>High-voltage components</h3><p>Magnetron, capacitor, and diode failures require a trained technician with proper discharge procedure. This is not a DIY repair. The labor reflects the safety requirements &mdash; not just the time to install the part.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#127991;</div><h3>Brand and OEM part cost</h3><p>Generic magnetrons exist but OEM parts are preferred for longevity and fit. Miele, Bosch, and Sharp built-in units use proprietary components at premium pricing &mdash; quoted separately so you see the real cost.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#128295;</div><h3>Installation access</h3><p>Countertop microwaves are easy to access. OTR units require working overhead and may need dismounting. Built-in drawer units require removing the drawer mechanism. Labor reflects actual access complexity.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#128204;</div><h3>Arcing &mdash; stop using immediately</h3><p>A microwave that sparks or arcs internally should not be used until repaired. Continued use can damage the magnetron and cavity beyond economic repair. Arcing is usually a waveguide cover issue &mdash; inexpensive to fix if caught early.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="sl">Repair vs. Replace</p>
    <h2>When to repair a microwave, when to replace it</h2>
    <p class="lead">The answer depends almost entirely on whether it&rsquo;s countertop or built-in. We give you the honest math after diagnosis.</p>
    <div class="rvr-grid">
      <div class="rvr-card repair">
        <h3>Repair makes sense when:</h3>
        <ul class="rvr-list">
          <li>Over-the-range unit &mdash; replacement requires installation</li>
          <li>Built-in or drawer unit &mdash; replacement requires cabinetry work</li>
          <li>Any unit with door latch, fuse, or turntable failure</li>
          <li>Countertop unit worth over $300 with minor failure</li>
          <li>Miele / Bosch built-in &mdash; these last 15+ years</li>
          <li>Arcing from waveguide cover &mdash; inexpensive fix</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="rvr-card replace">
        <h3>Replace makes more sense when:</h3>
        <ul class="rvr-list">
          <li>Budget countertop unit under $150 with magnetron failure</li>
          <li>Control board cost exceeds unit replacement value</li>
          <li>Interior cavity physically damaged from arcing</li>
          <li>Unit over 10 years old with major component failure</li>
          <li>Parts discontinued with no OEM availability</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

