      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Is it worth repairing a countertop microwave?</div><div class="faq-a">It depends on the failure. Door latch, fuse, and turntable repairs on any countertop unit are usually worth it. Magnetron and control board replacements on budget countertop units (under $150) often are not &mdash; repair cost can exceed unit value. We tell you the honest math before ordering parts.</div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">Are microwaves safe to repair?</div><div class="faq-a">A trained technician can repair microwaves safely. The danger is the high-voltage capacitor inside &mdash; it holds a lethal charge even when unplugged. Any repair beyond the door panel should be done by a technician with proper capacitor discharge procedures. Do not open the internal cavity yourself.</div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-q">My microwave is sparking. Is that dangerous?</div><div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; stop using it immediately. Sparking is usually caused by grease buildup on the waveguide cover, which is an inexpensive fix if caught early. Continued use damages the magnetron and interior cavity, turning a $100 repair into a much more expensive problem.</div></div>
